replyContent: It will probably help to update the satellite ephemeris files used by your phone's A-GPS (assisted GPS).  You can update the satellite ephemeris file with GPS RESET COM, free on Google Play.  Open that app, press GPS Tools, then push the big green reset button.

not have the ability to make its way with its own onboard electronic 
navigation system. Before leaving shore, I added my waterway waypoints

easily are stored in the Waypoint Manager. For my test use of this app, I

waypoint. I enjoyed the ability to record my track and hope to be able to

recommend it as a buy.

My review centers on the use of this app off the roadways and off the beaten path. I use it in conjunction with other apps in this role but it is by far my "go to favourite"  I am involved in metal detecting and although retired, my pre retirement skillset soon saw me being called on in the disposal of unexploded munitions in Australia's largest WWII training area (now slowly being developed for housing) that other detectorists find while looking for artifacts.  It is not uncommon for me to receive a SMS with a link containing co ordinates of a mortar round or a stash of grenades or similar and a reqest for prompt arrival.  Likewise it is not uncommon for me to hike many km into unbroken bushland from my car with an extensive kit to reach the site.   The moment I leave the car behind this fine app is running. Being not so young I take breaks often in the Australian heat and often have to double back on my path to get around unpassable terrain.  I use this app to navigate to the location, store the location of every item discovered and the amount of times this app has allowed me to backtrack to a rest area to retrieve a piece of equipment mistakenly left behind in dense bush defies belief. Currently it is running at a 100% batting average after 2 years plus.  At the end of the job with proper use it guides me back to the car via the shortest route.  It's so good I have converted the SGT head of the army UXO team whom I obviously call for the stuff too hard or unstable to a user.  It's also brilliant for any simple hiker or explorer or detectorist. It has more functions than I will ever use.  When I went looking for a waypointing app I knew exactly what I wanted, chose carefully and have never regretted the choice.  As a rule I don't pay for full version apps. I paid for this crying "hurry up and take my money!" Then again, this is way to good to be called an mere app. It is true engineered software.  It is highly featured and so brings me too my only niggle which is as an old guy I did have a preference for the simpler interface of the older versions but I can only counter by saying that as such a comprehensive package it does have a learning curve. It is effort well spent to follow that curve.  Long review? ..... Worthy product. In closing I will say I have no doubt this app has improved safety and even saved lives. Perhaps even my own. Although it has a lot of features, and does a fair job of tracking trails I hike, this software has significant bugs/errors.   The Map Trails screen gives one distance for a trail while the Altitude Profile gives a totally different (longer) distance, making the system's accuracy questionable.   In S.I. the Altitude Profile converts kilometers to meters but leaves the km unit on, making it look like you've hiked 1000 times as far. This error  is not present if using US measures.   Altitude is not stored as part of a trail node or waypoint and the Altitude Profile does not link back to nodes, leaving questions like "What was the highest/lowest part of that stretch?" unanswerable. Altitude of individual trail nodes is simply unavailable while altitude of waypoints must be calculated one at a time, which is clumsy and time-consuming. There is a lot about GPS Way points that I like but overall I think it needs further development.

replyContent: Hello Tony.  The issue is more of a phone issue than an app issue.   Trails much longer than yours will typically render instantly.  Problem is most likely due to other apps on your device  that are running inefficient background processes.  It is a trial and error process of deleting one app at a time to find the culprit. - DSS

Said compass needed calibrating so sorry
replyContent: Calibrate the compass by moving your phone in a figure 8 as shown in the calibrate message.  Or better, switch compass control from magnet to GPS.  GPS control is the preferred mode for our app because in GPS mode, the compass is not subject to error from metal and electromagnetic fields around you.

This is all for the app at V8.58. If there's something newer, that would be good to know. I run on a Nexus 5, Android version 5.1.1.
replyContent: Hello Del.  Only Google can update Google Maps. To update the non-Google Maps you should make an openstreetmap account and edit the map.  Changes are posted within 72 hours.  For navigation safety, all waypoint coordinates are final.  Capture your position as a waypoint when the accuracy is +/-30 ft or less on the first screen for maximum accuracy.

This program has about a dozen screen, with each screen dedicated to a function (e.g. compass, map of current location, sunset/sunrise). Each screen, in fact, is offered as a separate app as well, but there is no integration between the screens when bundled into a single app. For example, the compass shows the GPS coordinates, but when switching to the sunset/sunrise screen or GPS views, the app tries to get GPS signal all over again. When I selected Google street map to view current position, then going to trail view, it uses a different map again. The lack of integration, especially each screen must get its own GPS locking from scratch is the biggest problem.  Other useful ideas. - auto name the trail with current date and time - overhead satellite view shows the position of the sats, but not which is in use - sat strength shows individual signal, but doesn't show if the app got a good lock yet - in trail view, rotating the screen changes map type?  - why is the free version called Polaris Navigator and this paid version is called GPS Waypoint Navigator? Confusing...

replyContent: Arrow navigation is tied to GPS tracking. You must be moving for effective pointing (spinning around doesn't count). To delete: 1st screen→Waypoint Manager→Menu→DELETE WAYPOINT→TAP THE WAYPOINT TO DELETE.  You export from the Waypoint and Trail Manager Screens.  Tap Menu→Export or Email.  Please contact us if you have questions.

content: I can run GPS Waypoints Navigator in the background at the same time as running my tracker app & they complement very well. I make a set of waypoints for my hike (key milestones, difficult junctions, etc.) using Google Earth or old tracks.  The management of waypoints is a little clunky, but workable. I make a file for each hike.
replyContent:
You can now import as well as export kml files.  Imported files are viewable and navigable.  Export your kml files to a friend and he/she can navigate your favorite waypoints and trails just by tapping on an email attachment or a kml file in the device's file system.
-DS Software

content: Enter a waypoint and you're stuck with it for life? Hummm... I don't think so.
replyContent: 3 options for entering a waypoint:  Save current position, use map or enter coordinates.    To delete: Select Waypoint Manager- menu- Delete Waypoint then tap the waypoint you wish to delete- pretty easy... See the app help section if you are having difficulty reading the instructions or send us an email and we will walk you through it by phone.

content: Mapping functionality is weak...there isn't even a menu.
replyContent: There is a menu button at the bottom of all Google Maps.  Just push it.  The offline maps ( OpenStreetMap ) does not require a menu.  For enhanced map functionality set your map source to Google Maps in the App's Settings.

content: Works excellent on my electrify, but was having a problem on my nexus 7.  Wrote to the Dev  and a response was very quick, and very pleasant.  Found out that my GPS in my nexus was showing way off.   Dev was very friendly throughout, and have superb support.  Many thanks.

I work throughout North America designing RV Parks and Campgrounds.  We are often working with property that has not been surveyed yet so our fall back is to walk the property creating waypoints and trails.  The hard part is then getting them into a format that we use in CAD software.  In the past I've used a Garmin GPS and later a different software program on m;y phone.  I just did a study using this software for the first time and had great luck creating the trail but then I was not able to download the file.  I contacted the developer of the software and the went back and looked up when I had purchased the app.  It turned out that I needed to download the free upgrade and once that was done everything worked perfectly.  Thanks for the great service in solving my problem.  Homer Staves

Several things relegate this app to 'Nice Try'.  1 The mean use of display. On my tablet screen use is about one third of available size. The only background colour is Black. The font size is small. In all these limitations mean the app is next to impossible to use out of doors. 2 The display is only in Portrait (with one exception discovered). 3. Entering coordinates you have four options. When you choose Deg/Mins the next screen does not allow entry in this format. 4. An extra app is needed to use a paired wireless receiver. 5 The app crashes indoors unless you use a GPS simulator. 6 The algorithm used to 'join the dots' caused by intermittent reception produces some very inaccurate results. IMHO it deserves 4.5 for potential but only 2.5 for presentation

This app can't find any direction but south.  If I turn to any other direction the compass is always wrong. If I turn due east it shows southeast. If I turn due west it shows southwest.  And forget north. It can't find it. So that's 4 bucks down the drain. The free compass by Catch (?) works very well.  This thing gets no stars from me.  HTC Sensation and Nexus 7?
replyContent: Starting in version 5.11 an option is included that allows you to set magnetic compass reporting.  The magnetic compass, by default,  will now show deviation from True North instead of Magnetic North.  If you prefer the compass to show deviation from Magnetic North you can change the setting on the app's Settings screen.

content: This does exactly what it says on the tin and the support and updates speak for themselves
Very stupid app
Keeps crashing, when I ask for sun rise set times. Nexus 7
replyContent:
Robert, please update to version 4.63 to correct the issue.  If you are still having trouble email us at support@discipleskies.com
-Development Team

content: I used and liked this app for off trail hiking in the local parks. I wrote to the developers asking how to review duration and length of trails after they have been logged and I received a response almost immediately, indicating that the app did not support that capability but that they would add it at the next update. Less than a week later, the update arrived with the additions I had hoped for! Excellent app and amazing customer support!
It works perfectly. Good app, 5 stars

This is a great little program, a no frills classic GPS navigation tool for Android, like no other!  But would be even better with the following options:  24H time instead of AM/PM. Nobody uses AM/PM system in continental Europe!  Instead of "estimated arrival time" there should be an option to show "time left to arrival" instead, so that you could visualize "it takes me 00h20m to get to the waypoint" instead of "i'm arriving there at 10h30m, oh... and by the way, it's 10h10m now".  There should be an arrow

This works good on my razr max it works excellent. But on my Nexus 7 it does not work good. When I bring up the menu bar, I cannot get the different categories to work. It takes several tries to get the categories to come up right. If you could update this so it would work on my Nexus 7 I would give it a 5.

Using Samsung galaxy S3. Looks like app would be good if all functions worked. When in the settings page which has many tabs for help and other functions none of the tabs work. It looks like there are a lot of good functions but useless if they don't work. At this point I can not recommend. Save your money.
replyContent:
Hello Michael, Addition of the Android-Support Library to the app fixed this issue so we are closing this case.  Email us at support@discipleskies if you have any other concerns or questions.
-DS Developement Team

content: Needs to show GPS time. Otherwise pretty good app.

I have searched far and wide on the market and this applications stands out by far.  It is user friendly and smooth to use.  It isn't needlessly complicated and gets the job done really well. It's great that the arrow points to the waypoint itself, not to a offset from north, like other applications can. Being able to choose a waypoint from a satellite map makes it easy to find the point you are looking for, as you aren't necessarily choosing a waypoint near a road. The small installation cost is well worth the application, and means the developer can bring out more great applications :-) Thanks, Mark.
